You Nate can u make (what I call) a pre vacuum chamber. It's actually just a second vacuum chamber (pre vac) next to the chamber u are putting things in to test. (test vac) what you do is pull a vacuum on the pre vac chamber and keep the test vacuum chamber at atmosphere. Then when the pre vacuum chamber (that is bigger than the test vac) has a vacuum u close the valves of the test vacuum chamber to the atmosphere, and open the valve that is connected to the two tanks (the pipe that connects the two must be very wide so you have the least resistance) if you do it this way you get the effect of a vacuum in space.
The vacuum appears all at once and it's not just gradually with just the pump.

haven't watched but the answer is NO. Cinnamon is like a plant bark and will burn instead of melt like sugar, period. For cinnamon taste, you have to use a water soluble cinnamon flavoring. Things that won't melt as easy as the sugar (say, the slight bit of cornstarch that is used in all sugar as a declump agent) or won't melt at all like cinnamon will just clog up your sugar channels in your heating spinner cover, giving an inconsistent floss. Even chocolate has too many solids and will always burn or have a burnt taste in you try to spin it. Only solid, clearish sugars or sugar candies will spin into floss. And when you are making a big, pretty cloud of cotton candy on a cone or stick, don't wait for it to accumulate on the sides of the catch bowl; take it as it slings out from the spinner, holding your stick above the spinner, twisting the hole time; it will come off in one band or floss of melted sugar and you spin the stick (cone) in your hand like you were winding twine on a spool, like the streetcart vendor videos. And yeah, the top part of the catch bowl totally gets in the way; Take it off. Its just hot sugar. There you go, the perfect cotton candy. Enjoy.
